*1x1 count of northbound birds. A good handful were reluctant to cross the ocean and turned around at the point before immediately trying again, or heading back inland. Some of these could have returned later in the morning for a second try, but wouldn’t have much of an impact on the count if that was the case. If the RHWO is any indication of woodpecker behavior here, once the birds bail out and head back inland, they settle down and don’t come back.

Observation Details: *Witnessed two females viciously fighting over a stump with presumably some ants underneath.  As I was about to leave, I noticed a female NOFL feeding by probing into the dirt next to a stump. A second female came and landed nearby, and after about 1-2 minutes of posturing at each other, a switch flipped and they fought aggressively. The fight lasted 3-5 seconds, and after reviewing the photos it seemed pretty one sided, with the defender driving away the challenger. The winning flicker grabbed the other by the feathers on the nape, and it looks pretty vicious in the photos. The loser flew to a nearby tree, and seemed physically fine, if a little shell-shocked. It rested for a good minute or two.

Observation Details: Photo:

This bird has been visiting the yard since 12-24, but does not stay long and is very wary when in the yard. If other Flickers are present, it is chased off, especially by two intergrade males. He also visits early when the light is poor, so hard to catch good photos for field marker discernments. At first I was unsure if pure yellow-shafted. Today I was able to capture better photos and based on thick, bold chevron, thick black malars void of any red, beige-pink throat, neck, and cheeks, brown brow, and highlighter yellow-shafts on wings and tail, I believe I have a true yellow-shafted Flicker now intermittently joining the 10 individuals that have been visiting since early November. See photos for field markers and details.

Observation Details: There was quite a commotion at the base of a tree on the south side of the lake. A few flickers appeared to be fighting and were upset about something and then I realized one was snagged. Fishing line. The wing was tangled a bit and I cut the line off. Minor injury on the wing of the female and she flew off ok. I've handled and banded probably 7500 passerines and near passerines (i.e. woodpeckers, doves, etc.) over the years (I've held a master banding permit previously) but have banded few birds in the west. My first in hand red-shafted flicker. Injury was minor enough to release her.

Today I was able to capture better photos and based on thick, bold chevron, thick black malars void of any red, beige-pink throat, neck, and cheeks, brown brow, and highlighter yellow-shafts on wings and tail, I believe I have a true yellow-shafted Flicker now intermittently joining the 10 individuals that have been visiting since early November. See photos for field markers and details.

Observation Details: *Witnessed two females viciously fighting over a stump with presumably some ants underneath.  As I was about to leave, I noticed a female NOFL feeding by probing into the dirt next to a stump. A second female came and landed nearby, and after about 1-2 minutes of posturing at each other, a switch flipped and they fought aggressively. The fight lasted 3-5 seconds, and after reviewing the photos it seemed pretty one sided, with the defender driving away the challenger. The winning flicker grabbed the other by the feathers on the nape, and it looks pretty vicious in the photos. The loser flew to a nearby tree, and seemed physically fine, if a little shell-shocked. It rested for a good minute or two.

I think this Yellow-shafted flicker is the real deal.  He has the red crescent on the nape of his neck, black malar stripes, pale brown face and yellow shafts.  You can see all of this, except the yellow shafts, in the photo, but in flight I also confirmed the underside of the wings are yellow.  For the last two years I've had a female Yellow-shafted Flicker at our feeders; this is the first male.  In the second photo you can see the Yellow-shafted Flicker on the right and a sort of typical intergrade Norther Flicker on the left.  It has a small red crescent, but its other features are like a Red-shafted Flicker.

Media notes: Northern Flicker subspecies hybrid
Observation Details: Carburn Park has a large northern flicker population possibly due to the large number of cottonwood and poplar trees and the proximity to the river where I see these birds foraging along the gravel shore for aquatic insects. I see several subspecies hybrids particularly in this park. For example, this bird has the yellow flight feathers and mostly black malar of the yellow-shafted version. Its throat and cheek is gray however as for the red-shafted version. The malar is fringed in red further indicating hybridization.

Observation Details: I think this Yellow-shafted flicker is the real deal.  He has the red crescent on the nape of his neck, black malar stripes, pale brown face and yellow shafts.  You can see all of this, except the yellow shafts, in the photo, but in flight I also confirmed the underside of the wings are yellow.  For the last two years I've had a female Yellow-shafted Flicker at our feeders; this is the first male.  In the second photo you can see the Yellow-shafted Flicker on the right and a sort of typical intergrade Norther Flicker on the left.  It has a small red crescent, but its other features are like a Red-shafted Flicker.

Observation Details: *1x1 count of northbound birds. A good handful were reluctant to cross the ocean and turned around at the point before immediately trying again, or heading back inland. Some of these could have returned later in the morning for a second try, but wouldn’t have much of an impact on the count if that was the case. If the RHWO is any indication of woodpecker behavior here, once the birds bail out and head back inland, they settle down and don’t come back.

*Witnessed two females viciously fighting over a stump with presumably some ants underneath.  As I was about to leave, I noticed a female NOFL feeding by probing into the dirt next to a stump. A second female came and landed nearby, and after about 1-2 minutes of posturing at each other, a switch flipped and they fought aggressively. The fight lasted 3-5 seconds, and after reviewing the photos it seemed pretty one sided, with the defender driving away the challenger. The winning flicker grabbed the other by the feathers on the nape, and it looks pretty vicious in the photos. The loser flew to a nearby tree, and seemed physically fine, if a little shell-shocked. It rested for a good minute or two.

The race C. a. chrysocaulosus is endemic to Cuba. This is one of the yellow-shafted forms which differs from eastern North American birds by the cheeks and throat being pale tan and contrasting with the grey crown, the mantle is olive-green, the rump is spotted and the tail is heavily barred and longer than that in northern birds, the ventral markings appear barred rather than spotted, and the wings are long and rounded. The male shows a black malar and red nape crescent.

Female landed in the Black Walnut and loudly sang a full repertoire of songs.  She flew to the failed 2022 nest cavity then near the 2021nest site.  Soon a probable male flew to a nearby tree and then near the female.  They began flying from tree to tree when another Flicker joined the chase for about one minute.  The original pair then flew around the entire yard, tree to tree, as the probable male chased the female.  The chases last well over five minutes.  At one point there nay have been four Flickers: two in the chase and two calling.

A week before 'E' and here's a probable. I don't think this is a false positive...I observed a male following female around from tree to tree. Got photo of them perching together. They sat on that branch for a few minutes before moving to another tree and doing the same thing.

Observation Details: *Witnessed two females viciously fighting over a stump with presumably some ants underneath.  As I was about to leave, I noticed a female NOFL feeding by probing into the dirt next to a stump. A second female came and landed nearby, and after about 1-2 minutes of posturing at each other, a switch flipped and they fought aggressively. The fight lasted 3-5 seconds, and after reviewing the photos it seemed pretty one sided, with the defender driving away the challenger. The winning flicker grabbed the other by the feathers on the nape, and it looks pretty vicious in the photos. The loser flew to a nearby tree, and seemed physically fine, if a little shell-shocked. It rested for a good minute or two.

Observation Details: This little bugger first showed up at the school a couple days after one was reported by the Graton Casino, and ever since then, I've been chasing it down early in the mornings with my little phone camera hoping to get a shot good enough to ID it off of. This was quite a challenge since I only had a 20-minute window every day before school started. My very first impressions of it were that it has the characteristic gold shafts that stood out against the wings and tails of the normal red-shafted flickers it likes to hang out with. After seeing those wings first, it took me a while to get a clear view of the head, which did end up having a tan face and gray nape, with no mustache marks. Today it decided to go off its normal course and fly into a patch of trees that are very easy to walk around, and I finally got decent photos, which will be added shortly.

Two Flickers noticed in our yard. They were about 3 metres apart but then the male (black malar) violated social distancing rules by hopping over to female with its head held very high and the red on the back of the head puffed out dramatically. It also appeared to be offering the female (no black malar, just brown face) something, but she turned away and the display ended. The male flew up to our fence in the direct sunlight (setting) and the red patch on the head glowed very brightly.

Yellow-shafted female

This was a pretty confusing bird, I'm not gonna lie. It definitely had yellow wing shafts and tail, but its face was mostly gray, with a faint brown mustache which is characteristic of red-shafted or gilded, but not yellow-shafted flickers. It's possible this is a YS/RS intergrade, but I think it is just as possible that this is a RS/Gilded hybrid as gilded flickers breed in the joshua tree forests of Nevada, closer than any yellow-shafted breeders. I'm sorry I couldn't get a better shot of the crown to assess its amount of cinnamon, but she wasn't interested in coming out to play.  Interestingly, the refuge manager said he's seen this (or a) yellow bird in this area the past two years. But I don't know any more details than that.

Media notes: Intergrade Northern Flicker [female]: The "V" Crescent on the nape of her neck looks almost embroidered....she's much darker than the R.S. Northern Flickers.
Observation Details: Excited! First noticed this intergrade because she is much darker than the other Northern Flickers at the feeder. Then we witnessed a bit of a challenge between a male R.S. and this darker Flicker. Observed and took photos, then realizing what she was by the red "V" crescent on the nape of her neck [an ID mark for Yellow-shafted]. There is no black malar which means she's a female, and she has salmon-red feathers [an ID mark for Red-Shafted] Wondering if she's a young one because the red crescent is quite small, but we don't know for sure. The 3 finally settled on their own feeding stations, but it was fascinating to watch this all play out this morning!!!

Observation Details: There was quite a commotion at the base of a tree on the south side of the lake. A few flickers appeared to be fighting and were upset about something and then I realized one was snagged. Fishing line. The wing was tangled a bit and I cut the line off. Minor injury on the wing of the female and she flew off ok. I've handled and banded probably 7500 passerines and near passerines (i.e. woodpeckers, doves, etc.) over the years (I've held a master banding permit previously) but have banded few birds in the west. My first in hand red-shafted flicker. Injury was minor enough to release her.

Media notes: Intergrade male (left) with second male.
Observation Details: Intergrade female (red nape mark plus red shafts and gray face with brown malar) on stump near parking lot. Nearby, an intergrade male (subtler red nape, plus red malar and shafts, and gray face) was interacting with a second male, probably closer to a pure red-shafted. Male interactions were silent, and not terribly intense. Mostly just face-to-face standoffs and short flights away from each other. It's not clear if anyone was 'winning'--neither consistently displaced the other. I tried to convince myself non-intergrade male was an immature with a slightly shorter bill and less well-developed malar mark, but I finally decided it wasn't clear from photos.
